title: For Sale:  Heckler & Koch pistol collection for an HK Collector
postcontent:
I have two H&K VP70 Z’s if you are not familiar with what this pistol is then he is a short history lesson. 
It was the first polymer-framed pistol, 12 years before the Glock 17. The VP70 uses a spring-loaded striker like a Glock, instead of a conventional firing pin. It is double action only so the trigger pull is relatively heavy. In lieu of a blade front sight, the VP70 uses a polished ramp with a central notch in the middle to provide the illusion of a dark front post. The VP70 does have a manual safety. It is the circular button located immediately behind the trigger and is a common cross-block safety. The "Z" designates the civilian variant is a semiautomatic only version. The VP70 was produced from 1970 until 1989. Four hundred VP-70 Z pistols were made chambered in 9×21mm IMI; these samples were made primarily for the civilian market of Italy, where the use of the 9×19mm Para is a sole privilege of military and law enforcement agencies. 
One of the two pistols is chambered in 9x19mm Para and the other is chambered in 9x21mm. For the pistols one comes with two magazines and the other comes with three. I believe all are 21 round magazines. The 9x19mm comes in a 1970’s pristine box that is still dark grey, magazine loader tool, has the original target from the factory in a wax package and the original operation manual. The 9x21mm comes in lighter grey more warn box that is still strong just lighter than the other. Included with this is 500 rounds of 9x21mm ammunition. 

Thank you for looking and if you have any questions please let me know. 
Sorry not interested in any trades at this time.

16" carbine is Rock River Arms. Heavy 5.56mm 1/9 twist barrel.  Chrome bcg, BCM Med charging handle, Midwest Industries 15" free float rail. Magpul RVG and MBUS, Vortex flash hider, Hogue pistol grip. Carbine gas system.  About 1500rds fired. Solid and reliable workhorse carbine. Mild wear from normal use such as scratches and dings. 

20" DMR is a Loki upper on a forged 80% lower. The lower was one of the first I have done and the cuts are a little rough, however the rifle has run flawlessly. I've put about 500rds through it. Barrel is fluted stainless 20" medium contour 1/8 twist with 5.56mm chamber. Standard BCG. A1 length stock with storage compartment. Hogue pistol grip. BCM Large charging handle. Troy industries 15" free float rail. Magpul RVG and MBUS. KNS anti rotation pins. Phantom flash hider. Standard trigger group with "garage" style tune to lighten the single stage trigger.  Was supposed to be a temporary thing until I could afford a quality trigger, but I haven't upgraded that yet. However,  this trigger has worked fine for me. Occasional light primer strikes on cheap steel case ammo with hard primers. Has fired every quality brass cased round I have fed it. I think I have some spare FCG parts lying around which I will throw in if I can find them. 1.5" nylon Web sling with quick detach swivel included. The upper was Duracoated OD green and FDE from the factory.  The lower was Gunkoted OD green using bake on enamel from Brownells. Rifle has some wear from normal use. Very unique looking rifle,  always a head turner at the range.

From the factory: The KSG is our first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape and design are similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9lbs and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1″ overall length and an 18.5″ cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 6 rounds of 12 gage 3″ shells each, for a total capacity of 6 6 1 (7 per tube if using 2-3/4″ shells). The simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The lever can be positioned in the center detent in order to easily clear the chamber without feeding another round from either magazine. A cross bolt style safety blocks the sear, and the pump release lever is located in front of the trigger guard. The pump includes an under Picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, or a light or laser. The included top Picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.

title: For Sale:  KEL-TEC KSG 12 gauge Shotgun Pump | Black Keltec GEN 2
postcontent:
This is a new Keltec Pump Shotgun in 12 gauge. It is new unfired direct from the factory. This is serious fire power.

From the factory: The KSG is our first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape and design are similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9lbs and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1″ overall length and an 18.5″ cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 6 rounds of 12 gage 3″ shells each, for a total capacity of 6 6 1 (7 per tube if using 2-3/4″ shells). The simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The lever can be positioned in the center detent in order to easily clear the chamber without feeding another round from either magazine. A cross bolt style safety blocks the sear, and the pump release lever is located in front of the trigger guard. The pump includes an under Picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, or a light or laser. The included top Picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.
